**** Balance the following chemical equation:

{eq}\text{PbS + H}_{2} \longrightarrow \text{H}_{2} \text{SO}_{4} + \text{Pb}

{/eq}

**

**

To balance the given chemical equation, we need to ensure that the number of atoms of each element is equal on both sides of the equation.

**STEP 1: Count the initial number of atoms**

{eq}\displaystyle

\begin{align}

\text{PbS}_{(s)} + \text{H}_{2}(g) & \underset{\mathrm{(initial)}}{\longrightarrow}  \text{H}_{2} \text{SO}_{4}(g) + \text{Pb}(s)  \\

\text{No. of P} &= 1  &  \text{No. of P} &=  1 \\

\text{No. of S} &= 1  &  \text{No. of S} &=  1 \\

\text{No. of H}   &=   2 & & \text{No. of H}   &=   2 \\

\text{No. of O} &=  4 & & \text{No. of O}  &=   4

\end{align}

{/eq}

**STEP 2: Balance the Pb**

Since the number of Pb atoms is already equal on both sides of the equation, we can leave it as is.

**STEP 3: Balance the S**

{eq}\displaystyle

\begin{align}

\text{PbS}_{(s)} + \text{H}_{2}(g) & \underset{\mathrm{(initial)}}{\longrightarrow}  \text{H}_{2} \text{SO}_{4}(g) + \text{Pb}(s)  \\

1\text{ } \text{PbS} &\overset{\rightharpoontimes_1}{\longrightarrow}  1\text{ } \text{H}_{2} \text{SO}_{4} & \text{Yes.} \\

&&& \text{Yes}  \\

&&& \text{Yes} \\

&&& \text{Yes}

\end{align}

{/eq}

Now, the number of S atoms is equal on both sides of the equation.

**STEP 4: Balance the H**

{eq}\displaystyle

\begin{align}

\text{PbS}_{(s)} + \text{H}_{2}(g) & \underset{\mathrm{(initial)}}{\longrightarrow}  \text{H}_{2} \text{SO}_{4}(g) + \text{Pb}(s)  \\

\text{Yes}  &\underset{\smile}{\longleftarrow} \text{Yes}  \\

\frac{2}{2}\text{ H}_{2} & + \text{H}_{2} & \underset{\rightharpoontimes_1}{\longrightarrow} \text{H}_{2} \text{SO}_{4} +  \text{Pb}  \\

\text{Yes}  &\underset{\smile}{\longleftarrow} \text{Yes}  \\

\end{align}

{/eq}

Now, the number of H atoms is equal on both sides of the equation, with the coefficients being 1/2. To balance this, we multiply the entire equation by 2:

{eq}\displaystyle

\text{PbS}_{(s)} + 2\text{H}_{2}(g) & \underset{\mathrm{(initial)}}{\longrightarrow}  2 \text{H}_{2} \text{SO}_{4}(g) + 2 \text{Pb} \\

\text{Step 5: Balance the O}

{eq}\displaystyle

\begin{align}

2\text{H}_{2} &+ \text{H}_{2}  + 2 \text{Pb}  \\

4\text{O} &  + 4 \text{O} &  && + \text{O} & + \text{O} \\

\implies \text{H}_{2} &\text{ }\!\!:\!\!\text{ O} =  4     \implies \text{H}_{2} &\text{ }\!\!:\!\!\text{ O} = 4   \\

\end{align}

{/eq}
